description.value: Egyptian terracotta flask. Lentoid (lens-shaped) flask, with a flattened circular body, both sides decorated in relief with an angular rosette surrounded by a double moulding containing a succession of small crescents and an outer notched ring. The neck of the flask has a double bulge and a mouth with a moulded rim; below the mouth a palmette extends over the decorated sides to reach the rosette. On each side of the neck are ring-handles with lower terminals of bolster form; two non-functional matching bolster feet are placed at the bottom. Two-piece mould. A patch of pitch-like substance (pine pitch or bitumen?) adheres to one side, probably sealing a hole. The flask rattles, with something that is too large to come out of the neck, probably part of the body repaired with the pitch. Red Nile silt with abundant fine mica, quartz and white and red inclusions. Covered with an overall red slip: Memphis Black Ware, fired in an oxidizing atmosphere.

Lentoid (lens-shaped) flask, with a flattened circular body, both sides decorated in relief with an angular rosette surrounded by a double moulding containing a succession of small crescents and an outer notched ring. The neck of the flask has a double bulge and a mouth with a moulded rim; below the mouth a palmette extends over the decorated sides to reach the rosette. On each side of the neck are ring-handles with lower terminals of bolster form; two non-functional matching bolster feet are placed at the bottom. Two-piece mould. A patch of pitch-like substance (pine pitch or bitumen?) adheres to one side, probably sealing a hole. The flask rattles, with something that is too large to come out of the neck, probably part of the body repaired with the pitch. Red Nile silt with abundant fine mica, quartz and white and red inclusions. Covered with an overall red slip: Memphis Black Ware, fired in an oxidizing atmosphere.

description.value: Terracotta flask in the form of Isis riding a goose: the flask is in good condition, except for the nose of Isis and the base ring, which are damaged. The vessel was made in a two-piece mould; the fabric is micaceous brown Nile silt, covered with a black slip (Memphite Black Ware). This vessel shows Isis riding side-saddle on a goose, wrapping her arms around the neck of the bird, whose head turns back and leans on her right arm. Isis has a row of short corkscrew locks around her forehead, and then longer curls that fall on to her shoulders. She wears a fringed garment, knotted at her breasts, that covers her back and buttocks, but leaves her legs exposed. At the back the work is less detailed, and the goose's wing is extended. A handle runs from the head of Isis to her back, and on top of her head is the short, flaring mouth of the vessel. Below the group is a series of long, pointed leaves rising from the base ring.

description.value: A terracotta flask, modelled in the round, in the form of Bes riding a horse, which has fallen to its knees. Bes is in Macedonian armour, a cuirass over a tunic with short sleeves and pteryges. He wears a chlamys fastened with a brooch at his breast; his headgear is lost together with the mouth of the vessel. Just below the fastening of the cloak, the handle of a sword is shown with the upper part of its scabbard, worn almost horizontally, the lower part hidden by the horse's mane. He wears anklets or boots. His body and head are turned to his right, and he rests his right hand on the horse's crupper. His left arm is raised, at the back, to the top of the horse's neck. The horse, whose head is lost, has a double breastband with many pendants; the saddle is well indicated, and the girth is double. The rear legs are oddly rendered, giving the impression of both being shown on each side. The tail is luxuriant and reaches to the low oval plinth supporting the group. Two-piece mould. Micaceous dark brown-grey Nile silt, covered with a black slip: Memphis Black Ware.

description.value: Pottery ring flask: with a globular body, long cylindrical neck and two vertical handles. It is made of an extremely hard, dense, gritty paste containing quantities of fine to coarse sand, and with many fine rectangular impressions on the surface from burnt-out organic matter. It was thrown in three parts, neck, front and back. The neck was inserted into body and body joined along side, the handles applied. The surface covered is with self slip and polished to reddish yellow. There is painted decoration of a guilloche pattern in black outline with red filling on body, and beneath the handles foliage of leaves and tendrils in red and black.

description.value: Lentoid flask with two vertical handles: the body is opaque amethyst glass with glossy surface. On the rim is a prefabricated white and amethyst cord. The body decorations are in white, yellow, and turquoise-blue and are of fine quality. The handles were overlaid with five white and yellow threads.  One handle is lost, two gaps in the body. On one side at the shoulder there is a small patch indicating misfiring - a rare detail in Egyptian vessels. A small section at the base of the handle is concave. Within the vessel is a small packet of amethyst glass fragments presumably found with the flask.

description.value: Large end-flute: with four evenly spaced holes on one side.  The cutting at both ends of the instrument is rough and there appears to have been no attempt at bevelling the mouthpiece; the shaping of the holes is likewise crude.  There is a pronounced node about halfway down the instrument and traces of white paint on the surface and a diagonal criss-cross decoration. Traces of resin are visible inside the mouthpiece end of the instrument.  The bore is cylindrical and varies considerably.

description.value: Wooden folding-stool. The well cut and finished base rails are cylindrical and without further decoration. The folding legs each terminate in a head of a duck or goose. These heads are carefully carved, with the eyes and nostrils inlaid with ivory; there are also long thin triangular pieces of ivory inlaid into the neck of the bird. The third part is the seat rails. To these would have been attached a piece of leather to serve as the seat, and many traces of the leather remain on the underside of the rails.
